(
<figureCitation id="92C42A4118751371AA805D11FDF51B4C" box="[402,522,1796,1819]" captionStart="FIGURES 13 – 18" captionStartId="3.[151,258,1099,1121]" captionTargetBox="[151,1430,200,1071]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[151,1436,191,1078]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 13 – 18. Polia ssp. female genitalia. 13. P. h o f e r sp. n., female, paratype, China, N. Sichuan, prep. OP 3247 f, (OPB); 14. P. hofer sp. n., female, paratype, China, N. Sichuan, prep. GB 8687 f, (GBG / ZSM); 15. P. h o f e r sp. n., female, paratype, China, N. Sichuan, prep. GB 8689 f, (GBG / ZSM); 16. P. costirufa, female, holotype, China Batang [Tibet], W. Sichuan, GB 4497 f, (ZFMK); 17. P. c o s ti r u f a, female, China, W. Sichuan, Shaluli Shan, OP 3245 f, (OPB); 18. P. costirufa, female, China, W. Sichuan, Litang, GB 8705 f, (GBG / ZSM)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/258183/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="580">
Figs 
<number id="BC3724E318751371AAD85D11FDF51B4C" box="[458,522,1796,1819]" pageId="3" pageNumber="580" value="14.0" valueMax="15.0" valueMin="13.0">13-15</number>
</figureCitation>
). Papillae anales small, rectangular in shape, moderately hairy; apophyses anteriores short but strong; apophyses posteriores very short, but strong; ostium bursae widely calyculate; antrum large, elliptical in shape with small, conical lateral processes on both sides; cervix bursae large, left side with a large, flat, heavily sclerotised “pocket” with rather smooth surface, other parts strongly ribbed, corpus bursae moderately large, membranous, more-or less elliptical in shape.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="42E5654F18751376ABD55DA4FBDD1C86" lastPageId="4" lastPageNumber="581" pageId="3" pageNumber="580" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph id="0A4036C418751376ABD55DA4FBDD1C86" blockId="3.[151,1436,1276,2027]" lastBlockId="4.[151,1436,152,279]" lastPageId="4" lastPageNumber="581" pageId="3" pageNumber="580">
<emphasis id="388BEAD618751371ABD55DA4FE1D1B9F" bold="true" box="[199,482,1969,1992]" pageId="3" pageNumber="580">Biology and distribution</emphasis>
. Very large numbers of males and females were collected at ultraviolet light during a single cold night on 
<date id="7E41100418751371AA7D5DC1FE341BBC" box="[367,459,2004,2027]" pageId="3" pageNumber="580" value="1922-04">
<number id="BC3724E318751371AA7D5DC1FE751BBC" box="[367,394,2004,2027]" pageId="3" pageNumber="580" value="22.0">22</number>
April
</date>
, 
<quantity id="CD079B2118751371AAC45DC1FDD91BBC" box="[470,550,2004,2027]" metricMagnitude="1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.1181" pageId="3" pageNumber="580" unit="in" value="2015.0">2015 in</quantity>
a remote part of west China’s Sichuan Province near the Maoxian. 
<taxonomicName id="CDFF4D4718751371AFE65DC6FA931BBC" box="[1268,1388,2003,2027]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Polia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="580" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hofer">
<emphasis id="388BEAD618751371AFE65DC6FA931BBC" box="[1268,1388,2003,2027]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="580">Polia hofer</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was collected at an altitude of 
<number id="BC3724E318721376AAA15A8DFE171CF8" box="[435,488,152,175]" pageId="4" pageNumber="581" value="1800.0">1800</number>
meters in a mountain river dry valley sparsely covered by mixed forests dominated by various deciduous trees and bushes (
<figureCitation id="92C42A4118721376A90E5AAFFD961C86" box="[540,617,186,209]" captionStart="FIGURE 19" captionStartId="4.[151,244,1317,1339]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,333,1296]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[151,1436,333,1297]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 19. China, N. Sichuan, 20 km N. Maoxian, H- 1820 m, N 31 ° 46.310 ’, E 103 ° 42.898 ’, type locality of P. h o f e r sp. n." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/258184/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="581">
Fig. 
<number id="BC3724E318721376A95C5AAFFD961C86" box="[590,617,186,209]" pageId="4" pageNumber="581" value="19.0">19</number>
</figureCitation>
) where it was the most common noctuid.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="42E5654F18721376ABD55AC8FDBD1D40" pageId="4" pageNumber="581" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="0A4036C418721376ABD55AC8FDBD1D40" blockId="4.[151,1436,152,279]" pageId="4" pageNumber="581">
<emphasis id="388BEAD618721376ABD55AC8FEB81CA3" bold="true" box="[199,327,221,244]" pageId="4" pageNumber="581">Etymology.</emphasis>
The new species is named in the honour of the 
<taxonomicName id="CDFF4D4718721376A86A5AC8FC491CA3" box="[888,950,221,244]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Polia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="580" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hofer">Hofer</taxonomicName>
family (Rosa, Franz and Thomas) (Baden, 
<collectingCountry id="72E8765418721376AB855B15FF151D40" box="[151,234,256,279]" name="Austria" pageId="4" pageNumber="581">Austria</collectingCountry>
), for their merits in entomology.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
